"Maltais-Landry G., Maranger R., Brisson J., Chazarenc F.","Greenhouse gas production and efficiency of planted and artificially aerated constructed wetlands",2009,"Environmental Pollution","157","3",,"748","754",,,10.1016/j.envpol.2008.11.019,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-58649091762&partnerID=40&md5=889dffdf630c076e10c8728533f60cff","Département des sciences biologiques, Université de Montréal, 90, rue Vincent-D'Indy, Montréal (Que.), H2V 2S9, Canada; Institut de recherche en biologie végétale, Université de Montréal, 4101, rue Sherbrooke Est, Montréal (Que.), H1X 2B2, Canada","Maltais-Landry, G., Département des sciences biologiques, Université de Montréal, 90, rue Vincent-D'Indy, Montréal (Que.), H2V 2S9, Canada, Institut de recherche en biologie végétale, Université de Montréal, 4101, rue Sherbrooke Est, Montréal (Que.), H1X 2B2, Canada; Maranger, R., Département des sciences biologiques, Université de Montréal, 90, rue Vincent-D'Indy, Montréal (Que.), H2V 2S9, Canada; Brisson, J., Département des sciences biologiques, Université de Montréal, 90, rue Vincent-D'Indy, Montréal (Que.), H2V 2S9, Canada, Institut de recherche en biologie végétale, Université de Montréal, 4101, rue Sherbrooke Est, Montréal (Que.), H1X 2B2, Canada; Chazarenc, F., Institut de recherche en biologie végétale, Université de Montréal, 4101, rue Sherbrooke Est, Montréal (Que.), H1X 2B2, Canada","Greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions by constructed wetlands (CWs) could mitigate the environmental benefits of nutrient removal in these man-made ecosystems. We studied the effect of 3 different macrophyte species and artificial aeration on the rates of nitrous oxide (N2O), carbon dioxide (CO2) and methane (CH4) production in CW mesocosms over three seasons. CW emitted 2-10 times more GHG than natural wetlands. Overall, CH4 was the most important GHG emitted in unplanted treatments. Oxygen availability through artificial aeration reduced CH4 fluxes. Plant presence also decreased CH4 fluxes but favoured CO2 production. Nitrous oxide had a minor contribution to global warming potential (GWP &lt; 15%). The introduction of oxygen through artificial aeration combined with plant presence, particularly Typha angustifolia, had the overall best performance among the treatments tested in this study, including lowest GWP, greatest nutrient removal, and best hydraulic properties. © 2008 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Artificial aeration; Horizontal subsurface constructed wetlands; Macrophytes; Methane; Nitrous oxide","Artificial aeration; Green house gas (GHG) emissions; Greenhouse gas production; Horizontal subsurface constructed wetlands; Macrophytes; Mesocosms; Natural wetlands; Nitrous oxide; Nutrient removal; Oxygen availability; Typha angustifolia; Anesthetics; Carbon dioxide; Gas emissions; Gases; Global warming; Greenhouse gases; Greenhouses; Leakage (fluid); Methane; Nitrogen oxides; Nutrients; Oxygen; Wetlands; carbon dioxide; methane; nitrous oxide; oxygen; aeration; constructed wetland; gas production; global warming; grass; greenhouse gas; macrophyte; mesocosm; methane; mitigation; nitrous oxide; aeration; article; biosynthesis; constructed wetland; controlled study; environmental management; greenhouse effect; greenhouse gas; macrophyte; nonhuman; nutrient availability; oxygen supply; species difference; Typhaceae; Air; Biodegradation, Environmental; Carbon Dioxide; Ecology; Ecosystem; Gases; Greenhouse Effect; Methane; Nitrous Oxide; Plants; Poaceae; Seasons; Typhaceae; Water Pollutants, Chemical; Water Purification; Wetlands; Typha angustifolia",,"carbon dioxide, 124-38-9, 58561-67-4; methane, 74-82-8; nitrous oxide, 10024-97-2; oxygen, 7782-44-7; Carbon Dioxide, 124-38-9; Gases; Methane, 74-82-8; Nitrous Oxide, 10024-97-2; Water Pollutants, Chemical",,,,"American Public Health Association (APHA), American Water Works Association (AWWA), Water Environment Federation (WEF), (2005) Standard Methods for the Examination of Water and Wast